
A. Problem Statement & Motivation

Finding new music that suits your tastes is a major difficulty for listeners in the large and constantly growing era of digital music. Although several commercial platforms have developed sophisticated recommendation algorithms, these algorithms are typically ineffective. There is a growing interest among academics and researchers in understanding the fundamental mechanisms of musical similarity and in investigating state-of-the-art recommendation algorithms. By developing and assessing a music similarity model, we hope to directly address this problem. 
The community of music lovers interested in investigating music discovery beyond mainstream channels is the project's primary client/benefactor. We aim to enable these users to discover new artists and songs from the Free Music Archive (FMA), a vast and varied collection of non-commercial music, by developing a recommendation engine accessible to the general public. Providing a more transparent and varied music discovery experience, supporting the hobbyists, and carrying out thorough research and comparisons between different machine learning approaches and predictive models.
There are a few prior studies on this topic that may help to inform our approach. For example, methods such as cosine similarity applied to audio data are frequently used in Content-Based Music Recommendation; this approach will serve as our baseline. Although it frequently fails to capture more complex associations, it is comparable to early recommendation systems. 
We also plan to explore the Siamese Network, a more sophisticated method that uses deep learning to learn finer feature representations. By directly comparing these conventional techniques with contemporary Gen AI strategies, such as employing embeddings from Large Language Models and developing a multimodal model, this project sets itself apart. In the context of music similarity recommendation engine, this direct comparison is going to assess whether Gen AI's semantic comprehension can perform better than our audio-feature-based models.



B. Data Strategy
For this study, we will be using the Free Music Archive (FMA) dataset, which is accessible to the public. A large series of CSV files containing the data is supplied.

Repository: https://github.com/mdeff/fma

