raw_echonest.csv 14,512 250 ~ 47KB
raw_artists.csv 16,916 25 ~ 13KB
raw_albums.csv 15,234 19 ~ 23KB
raw_genres.csv 164 5 ~ 6KB


Features and Data Types
The main part of our analysis will use the audio features provided in the raw_echonest.csv file, which are all numerical. 

•acousticness: Confidence measure of whether the track is acoustic

•danceability: How suitable a track is for dancing

•energy: Perceptual measure of intensity and activity

•instrumentalness: Predicts whether a track contains vocals or not

•liveness: Identifies the presence of an audience in the recording 

•speechiness: Detects the presence of words 

•tempo: Estimated tempo and beats per minute

•valence: Musical positiveness by track

We will also use this data with categorical variables from other files, such as track_title, artist_name, and genre_title. There is no single predefined target variable; our goal is to generate a similarity score or ranking between tracks.




Preprocessing Plan
1. Data Merging: For convenience's sake, we will have the five CSV files combined into a single, cohesive dataset. This will provide a comprehensive overview of each track, including audio characteristics, artist details, and genre categorization.

2. Missing Values: Because some of the tracks have the Echonest audio features, dealing with missing values will be a bit difficult/time consuming. Our approach will be to concentrate our modeling attempts on this subset of 14,512 tracks with full feature data. This will help ensure that every model is trained and analyzed using reliable data. 

3. Normalization: To make sure the audio characteristics are on the same scale, we will perform Z-score normalization. Which will hopefully help us with neural network training and KNN in the long run.

4. Categorical Encoding: In order to be in our models, categorical characteristics like genre will be one-hot encoded. For the gen AI models, we will also create textual descriptions by concatenating track metadata. For example, "Track: [title] by [artist], Genre: [genre], Energy: [value]").

5. Data Splitting: The processed dataset will be divided into training (80%) and test (20%) sets.




C. Technical Methodology
1. Use pytorch to train a deep learning model on the data once it is validated and cleaned.
2. Set up an AI powered similarity detection agent using openAI and mini gpt4.5
3. Fine tune model parameters and system prompt for GPT bot
4. Once weights and prompts are finlaized deploy models to AWS
5. Integrate models into web application

D. Evaluation & Metrics
1. Compare similarity of AI model with deep learning model using a baseline model (TBD)
2. Design system to score the similarity measurements so we can rank models and agents.
3. Test model similarity by listening to songs outselves and see if we can feel the similarity "vibe" between the two.
4. Research current models/algorithms for song reccomendation and see if/how they determine similarity




